    "faqs": [
      {
        "question": "Is the radiation dose safe?",
        "answer": " Yes, it equals ~6 months of natural background exposure and is well within safe limits.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "Can I drive afterward?",
        "answer": " Absolutely—no sedation is involved.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "How soon will I get results?",
        "answer": " Same day; urgent cases within 30 minutes.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "Do I need a doctor’s prescription?",
        "answer": " Yes. Bring a signed requisition or have your physician email it to "
      },
      {
        "question": "When will I receive my results?",
        "answer": "At Cadabams Diagnostics, we pride ourselves on a quick turnaround. For urgent cases, a preliminary report can often be made available to your doctor shortly after the scan. A final, detailed report is typically ready within 24 hours."
      },
      {
        "question": " What is the main difference between this scan and one with contrast dye?",
        "answer": "The main difference is the use of an iodine-based intravenous (IV) dye. A **CT Lower Abdomen without Contrast** does not use dye and is excellent for seeing bones and calcifications like kidney stones. A scan with contrast uses dye to make blood vessels and certain organs or abnormalities stand out more clearly, which is better for evaluating tumors, infections, or vascular problems."
      }
    ],
